<task id="AIPU2-027" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Implement Privilege-Aware Retrieval — AI Search Security Filter</title>
    <phase>2B</phase>
    <tags>bff-api, security, ai-search</tags>
    <status>not-started</status>
    <estimated-effort>4 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>AIPU2-005</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>false</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    Extend the BFF's RagService to apply privilege_group_ids security filters on every Azure AI Search query.
    Currently, AI Search returns all indexed documents matching the semantic query regardless of the requesting
    user's matter access. This change ensures that cross-matter searches only return documents from matters
    the user is explicitly authorized to access. Group IDs are resolved from the caller's Azure AD token
    claims (group membership claims or on-demand Graph group lookup). This is a security-critical change —
    no document from an unauthorized matter must ever appear in retrieval results.
  </prompt>
  <role>Senior .NET security engineer with Azure AI Search filter syntax and Entra ID group claims experience.</role>
  <goal>
    Every RagService query includes a privilege_group_ids security filter. Documents not matching the user's
    group IDs are never returned. Cross-matter retrieval isolation is enforced at the search layer.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/constraints/auth.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/IRagService.cs</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/Graph/GraphClientFactory.cs</file>
      <file>docs/architecture/auth-azure-resources.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Read IRagService.cs and its implementation to understand the current search query construction, SearchOptions usage, and what fields are indexed in the AI Search index.</step>
    <step>Read auth.md and GraphClientFactory.cs to understand how user identity and group membership are currently resolved in the BFF request pipeline.</step>
    <step>Verify the AI Search index schema includes a privilege_group_ids field (string collection, filterable). If not present in the index definition, add it to the index schema update script (infrastructure/ai-search/) and document the schema change in the task notes. Do not apply schema changes to production — flag for deployment.</step>
    <step>Create IPrivilegeGroupResolver.cs interface with: Task&lt;IReadOnlyList&lt;string&gt;&gt; ResolveGroupIdsAsync(ClaimsPrincipal user, CancellationToken ct).</step>
    <step>Create PrivilegeGroupResolver.cs implementing IPrivilegeGroupResolver. Strategy: (1) Check JWT claims for "groups" claim (direct group IDs); (2) If groups claim absent or overage (200+ groups), call Microsoft Graph GET /me/memberOf to resolve transitively. Cache per user ID in IMemoryCache with 5-minute TTL.</step>
    <step>In RagService, inject IPrivilegeGroupResolver. Before building SearchOptions, call ResolveGroupIdsAsync and construct the OData filter: privilege_group_ids/any(g: g eq '{groupId1}') or privilege_group_ids/any(g: g eq '{groupId2}') ... Format using SearchFilter.Create for parameterized safety.</step>
    <step>Handle edge cases: empty group list → filter returns no documents (do not omit filter — log error and return empty result); Graph call failure → fail-closed (return empty results and log error, do not fall back to unfiltered search).</step>
    <step>Add OTEL counter ai_retrieval_privilege_filter_applied_total and ai_retrieval_privilege_filter_empty_result_total (when user has no matching group).</step>
    <step>Register IPrivilegeGroupResolver as scoped (per-request) in the DI container.</step>
    <step>Write unit tests: groups from claims applied as filter, groups from Graph fallback applied, empty group list returns empty results, Graph failure returns empty results (not unfiltered).</step>
    <step>Write an integration test (or clearly marked manual test checklist) that verifies a user without matter access receives zero results for that matter's documents.</step>
    <step>Run `dotnet build` and `dotnet test --filter "Privilege"` to verify.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>Every RagService query includes a privilege_group_ids filter — verified by examining SearchOptions in tests.</criterion>
    <criterion>Group IDs resolved from JWT claims when the "groups" claim is present.</criterion>
    <criterion>Graph API fallback used when groups claim is absent or overage (200+ groups).</criterion>
    <criterion>Empty group list results in an empty search result set, not an unfiltered query.</criterion>
    <criterion>Graph API failure results in empty search results and an error log (fail-closed).</criterion>
    <criterion>Group resolution results cached per user for 5 minutes.</criterion>
    <criterion>OTEL counters emitted correctly.</criterion>
    <criterion>Unit tests pass: `dotnet test --filter "Privilege"`.</criterion>
    <criterion>No unfiltered AI Search query can be issued through RagService after this change.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
